               <p>WILLIAM WIGGINS. I lost a coat on the 1st of October, from <placeName id="t18281023-264-crimeloc1529">Exmouth-street, Spafields</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18281023-264-crimeloc1529" type="placeName" value="Exmouth-street, Spafields"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18281023-264-crimeloc1529" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18281023-264-off1527 t18281023-264-crimeloc1529"></join>. Martha Richards gave it to the prisoner; I knew him by working for my father - I had seen the coat safe at nine o'clock that morning in my drawer.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281023-264-person1379">
                  MARTHA 
                  RICHARDS
               <interp inst="t18281023-264-person1379" type="surname" value="RICHARDS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-264-person1379" type="given" value="MARTHA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-264-person1379" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was at the prosecutor's house on the 1st of October, when the prisoner came and asked for a dark green great coat for Mr. Wiggins, which I gave him; he did not say where it was, but I knew, and gave it him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281023-264-person1380">
                  SIMON 
                  GILES
               <interp inst="t18281023-264-person1380" type="surname" value="GILES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-264-person1380" type="given" value="SIMON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-264-person1380" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . This coat was brought to me for sale on the 30th of September, by a young man resembling the prisoner - I never saw him before: I believe it to be him - I bought it for 18s.; he told me it was not his own, but a gentleman's, who had sent him, and if he did not approve of the price he should return before four o'clock.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281023-264-person1381">
                  GEORGE 
                  WADDINGTON
               <interp inst="t18281023-264-person1381" type="surname" value="WADDINGTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-264-person1381" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-264-person1381" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner was given into my custody on the evening of the 30th of September - he told me he had been sent by two other persons for the coat, and sold it at Mr. Giles - I went there, and got it.</p>
               <p>COURT to WILLIAM WIGGINS. Q. What day was it? A. I think it was the 1st of October.</p>
               <p>MARTHA RICHARDS. I think it was the 1st of October.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner. It is useless for me to make any defence - I am guilty. I had been out of employ five weeks, and was led into this by the prosecutor's own brother; I sold it to Mr. Giles, and the reason I made that agreement was to know if his brother would be satisfied.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18281023-264-verdict1530" type="verdictDescription">
